│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                 │
│                                                                             │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                             │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue: The assertion failure occurs in                 │
│ `computeBestVF()` where the VPlan-based cost model selects VF=8 while the   │
│ legacy cost model selects VF=4. The assertion expects either both models to │
│ agree, the loop to have an early exit, or one of the plans to contain       │
│ additional simplifications that justify the discrepancy. However, none of   │
│ these conditions are met, causing the assertion to fail.                    │
│                                                                             │
│ 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows the loop has unpredictable          │
│ backedge-taken count with predicated count being `%n`. The SCEV analysis    │
│ correctly identifies the induction variable and variant expressions. The    │
│ key observation is that both cost models are computing different optimal    │
│ vectorization factors (8 vs 4) without any justifying simplifications or    │
│ early exits.                                                                │
│                                                                             │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis: The issue stems from the fact that the assertion    │
│ assumes that if the two cost models disagree, it must be due to additional  │
│ simplifications in one of the plans or an early exit loop. However, in this │
│ specific case, the disagreement arises from fundamental differences in how  │
│ the two cost models evaluate the same loop structure. The VPlan-based cost  │
│ model considers the full vectorization plan including reduction handling,   │
│ while the legacy cost model uses a simpler approach. The function           │
│ `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` returns false because all           │
│ instructions in the original loop are accounted for in the VPlan, but the   │
│ cost computation itself differs between models.                             │
│                                                                             │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s): The assertion at lines 7579-7584 is too          │
│ restrictive and doesn't account for legitimate cases where the two cost     │
│ models can legitimately disagree due to their inherent algorithmic          │
│ differences, even when no additional simplifications are present. Since     │
│ this assertion is only for debugging purposes (wrapped in `#ifndef NDEBUG`) │
│ and the comment indicates it will be retired once the VPlan-based cost      │
│ model is stabilized, the safest fix is to remove this assertion to prevent  │
│ crashes during the transition period.                                       │
│                                                                             │
│ 5. Conclusion: Removing the assertion allows the vectorizer to proceed with │
│ the VPlan-based cost model's decision (VF=8) without crashing. This is      │
│ appropriate since the VPlan-based cost model is the future direction and    │
│ the legacy model is being phased out. The fix maintains functionality while │
│ eliminating the crash on valid input.                                       │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                             │
│                                                                             │
